                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Photographs and Film, 1937-1940.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>This collection contains thirty-one matted color photographs of Alaska, which Dr. Vogel has exhibited, as well as a video cassette copy of a film of a trip he made to Alaska (1937-1938). The photographs depict Juneau, Ketchikan, Fairbanks, and Circle City and include buildings, scenery, fish wheels, mining, and urban settings. The copy of the film includes views of Ketchikan, Juneau, and Valdez; gold mining; and scenes of the University of Alaska campus. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Unknown</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

               <mods xmlns="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3">
                  <recordInfo>
                     <recordOrigin>WorldCat:314197114</recordOrigin>
                     <recordContentSource>ISIL:AkU</recordContentSource>
                  </recordInfo>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Naske, Claus-M.</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/cre">Creator</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Claus-M. Naske papers, ca. 1959-</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>The Claus-M. Naske Papers consist of research files, manuscripts and supporting documentation, drafts and galley proofs, correspondence, committee files, transcripts of interviews, reports, proposals, meeting minutes, and publications. The bulk of the materials reflect Claus-M. Naske's role as tenured professor of History at the University of Alaska Fairbanks, and the activities he has undertaken in fulfillment of the requirements for a tenured professor to take part in teaching, research, and community service. Of special interest are the drafts and final manuscripts of Naske's many publications and the accompanying research files, which provide both resources for the study of the history of Alaska and insight into the research and writing processes leading to publication of scholarly articles and books. The collection also includes photographs of students and events at the University of Alaska in Fairbanks, taken by Naske in 1960 while a student working for that institution's public affairs office, and slides depicting Barrow, Alaska, taken by Naske in 1964-65 while teaching at a Bureau of Indian Affairs day school there. This is an ongoing collection. Please check with the archivist for more information. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>Unknown</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>

resource.title: Keith B. Mather Papers 1951-1986
resource.abstract: The Keith B. Mather papers include the typescript of his diary and photos from his cosmic ray expedition in the Himalayas in 1951; a daily log from his field work during the International Geophysical Year in Australia; his manuscript on the history of the Geophysical Institute along with a compilation of memoirs of the GI from others; and a document he wrote with Anna Schilling titled "Initiation, Evolution, and Production of Annual Reports on Research at the University of Alaska, Fairbanks" which describes the history of systematic reporting on research at the University.

                     <title>Papers, 1954-1993.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>The collection contains records relating to Miriam Carlson's work as an educator and administrator at Anchorage Community College. The collection is divided into three series. Series one contains personal papers of Miriam Carlson, including a photo, curriculum vitae, and her master's thesis. Series two contains records from Anchorage Community College. The series is divided into six subseries including planning documents, teacher's contracts, accreditation evaluations, budgets, reports to the Alaska State Legislature, and UAA-ACC merger documents. Series three includes publications from ACC, APU, Kenai Peninsula College, UAA, University of Alaska, and other sources. </abstract>
